  "text": "The core Kafka Streams architecture is defined by three fundamental classes in the apache/kafka repository:\n\n1. **Topology** (streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/Topology.java, line 60): A public class that represents a logical DAG (directed acyclic graph) of processing nodes. It encapsulates the complete stream processing topology consisting of source nodes (that consume Kafka topics), processor nodes (that transform records), and sink nodes (that write to Kafka topics). The Topology class provides methods to construct and describe this graph of nodes.\n\n2. **StreamsBuilder** (streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/StreamsBuilder.java, line 65): A public class that implements the high-level Kafka Streams DSL (Domain-Specific Language) for building topologies. It provides a convenient fluent API for developers to define stream processing logic without manually constructing low-level topology graphs. StreamsBuilder internally builds a Topology instance and delegates to InternalStreamsBuilder for DSL operations.\n\n3. **KafkaStreams** (streams/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/streams/KafkaStreams.java, line 161): A public class that implements AutoCloseable and serves as the runtime engine for executing a topology. It takes a Topology instance and StreamsConfig, manages the lifecycle of stream processing threads, handles state stores, and provides query capabilities for interactive state store access. This is the main entry point for running Kafka Streams applications."
}

